metadata.editComments: Changed E7 to be a borrowed chord instead of a secondary dominant, and changed key from F Lydian to F Major throughout the entire section. If a dominant 7 chord doesn't exactly lead to its intended destination (like A[m] for E7) I feel it's better to call it a borrowed chord, and if modulating to a mode that's only 1 step up/down the Circle of 5ths (like Lydian to Major) I'd prefer to just call the entire section one mode and borrow the notes. If someone smarter than me sees this, feel free to fix my work and explain how I'm wrong.

Changed first section to Bb Major: the chord progression feels like an extended ii-V-I in Bb, and F doesn't feel like the root to me. Changed second section to C Major, because of the bVI-bVII move at the end, and made the BÃ¸7(#5) a Bm7 chord. Lastly, changed the "F Lydian" section to simply be Major, as there are no defining characteristics of Lydian (yet).
